  "media loading": "",
  "React, in its purest form, is a library for building user interfaces. It's so simple that the entire mental model can be represented as a formula.": "",
  "calls a component": "",
  "A Gentle Reminder": "",
  "side effect": "",
  "API calls, manual DOM manipulation, using browser APIs like \u0000SKIP#143\u0000 or \u0000SKIP#144\u0000, or anything else that falls outside of simply calculating a View based on props and state is a side effect.": "",
  "This makes sense. When React renders, it does so with the goal of eventually updating the UI. This entire process needs to be so as fast as possible. If it weren't, regardless of the cause, there wouldn't be much value in using React.": "",
  "Rule #0": "",
  "When a component renders, it should do so without running into any side effects": "",
  "Now all of this sounds great –&nbsp;it's not terribly hard to see why React renders need to be pure calculations. The problem, as is usually the case, is reality often isn't so simple. Real applications aren't free of side effects. In fact, they're littered with them. So much so that I'd argue one of the biggest causes for bugs in any application is the mismanagement of side effects.": "",
  "If React didn't have an escape hatch for managing side effects which fall outside of the normal \u0000SKIP#145\u0000 paradigm, it would be a perfect project that we'd geek out over in Computer Science lectures, not a library that powers an increasing percentage of the internet.": "",
  "The React Industrial Complex": "",
  "(which are good, I might add)": "",
  "But if you can give me your pure, unadulterated brain,&nbsp;I'll give you a simple, easy to understand, and most importantly, correct mental model for managing side effects in React.": "",
  "Let's start off by looking at an app you're already familiar with, our greetings app we first saw in the post about how React re-renders.": "",
  "Sandbox - CodeSandbox": "",
  "As a reminder, our app works by sticking all our greetings in an array, and then having a piece of state that keeps track of the \u0000SKIP#150\u0000 of the greeting we want to display,": "",
  "We then have a button that when it's clicked, will increment the \u0000SKIP#151\u0000 or reset it back to \u0000SKIP#152\u0000 if we've reached the end of the array.": "",
  "This code is the perfect representation of the React model. It's simple, and pure, and as contrived as a Hallmark Christmas movie.": "",
  "Let's dip our toes into the murky yet alluring pool of complexity by adding a side effect to our app. Specifically, let's store the user's preferred greeting in local storage using the browser's \u0000SKIP#158\u0000 API. That way, when the user comes back to our app, even if they've closed the browser, they'll see the greeting they last selected.": "",
  "First, before we can worry about getting the value from local storage, we need to figure out how to add the item to local storage. Your intuition may be to do something like this.": "",
  "Now, whenever our app re-renders, local storage will get updated with the new \u0000SKIP#164\u0000 value,&nbsp;which we can then use in the future when establishing the initial state of the user's app.": "",
  "Interacting with \u0000SKIP#166\u0000 is a side effect and, regardless of how inconsequential or fast the side effect may seem, we need to keep it out of React's rendering flow.": "",
  "So how do we do that? This brings us to our next rule.": "",
  "Rule #1": "",
  "If a side effect is triggered by an event, put that side effect in an event handler": "",
  "As obvious as Rule #1 may seem, it's surprising how often it's neglected.": "",
  "The entire point of an event handler is to encapsulate the logic for an event. In doing so, in React, you naturally decouple that logic from React's rendering flow. Therefore, if a side effect is triggered by an event, put that side effect where you put all the other logic for that event, in its event handler.": "",
  "In the context of our app, that means moving our side effect, \u0000SKIP#167\u0000, into the event handler that triggers the event, \u0000SKIP#168\u0000.": "",
  "not involved with rendering": "",
  "Now that we've cached our \u0000SKIP#176\u0000 in local storage, we need to figure out how to get it back out when we set the initial \u0000SKIP#177\u0000 of our app.": "",
  "Your first intuition might be to do something like this.": "",
  "Every time \u0000SKIP#184\u0000 renders, our \u0000SKIP#185\u0000 side effect is going to be invoked, even though React will only use the result of that invocation on the initial render.": "",
  "Now you may be familiar with lazy state initialization. The idea is you can pass \u0000SKIP#186\u0000 a function that will only be called once, on the initial render, and the return value of that function will be used as the initial value for that state.": "",
  "Something like this.": "",
  "Rebellious of you, but we have rules for a reason. In this case, if you tried to server render our app (which is a totally reasonable thing you could do), you'd get an error since \u0000SKIP#192\u0000 isn't available on the server, obviously.": "",
  "If you adjusted your code to account for that, you'd end up with something like this.&nbsp;": "",
  "Which seems reasonable, but if there was a value in local storage on the initial render on the client, React would give you another error": "",
  "hacky ways": "",
